      <hedline>
        <hl1>Japan's Changing Face</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Dorian Benkoil letter reports that Japan is still insular, but has also become more open to wider world (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your article about foreigners debating with unusual candor on a popular Japanese television show (Tokyo Journal, April 27) struck a chord. In 1984, in Hamamatsu, Japan, I was often stared at, and little children would sometimes run away or ask to touch my hair.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your article about foreigners debating with unusual candor on a popular Japanese television show (Tokyo Journal, April 27) struck a chord. In 1984, in Hamamatsu, Japan, I was often stared at, and little children would sometimes run away or ask to touch my hair.</p>
        <p>When I visit today, I get nary a glance, and I am but one of many non-Japanese faces. Many Africans, Europeans and other foreigners work at Hamamatsu businesses. Yes, Japan is still insular, as the television program shows. But it has changed and become more open to the wider world.</p>
        <p>DORIAN BENKOIL  New York, April 27, 2000</p>
      </block>
